   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "f2bcf2ea-d903-41b6-b107-eddb0a5c90fb",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Iterating Callables - Lecture"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "6e5f029c-d111-401a-aa79-44b7d03f82a3",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Iterating over the return values of a callable\n",
    "\n",
    "Consider a callable that provides a countdown from some start value:\n",
    "\n",
    "countdown() -> 5\n",
    "countdown() -> 4\n",
    "countdown() -> 3\n",
    "countdown() -> 2\n",
    "countdown() -> 1\n",
    "countdown() -> 0\n",
    "countdown() -> -1\n",
    "...\n",
    "\n",
    "We now want to run a loop that will call countdown() until 0 is reached\n",
    "We could certainly do that using a loop and testing the value to break out of the loop once 0 is reached\n",
    "\n",
    "while True:\n",
    "    val = countdown()\n",
    "    if val == 0:\n",
    "        break\n",
    "    else:\n",
    "        print(val)\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "e02a8f00-e3eb-4a0f-b2a5-607bb92900a1",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "An iterator approach\n",
    "\n",
    "We could take a different approach using iterators and we can make it generic\n",
    "Making an iterator that knows two things:\n",
    "- the callable that needs to be called\n",
    "- a value (the sentinel) that will result in a StopIteration if the callable returns that value\n",
    "\n",
    "The iterator would then be implemented as follows:\n",
    "When next() is called\n",
    "- call the callable and get result\n",
    "- if result is equal to sentinel -> StopIteration and exhaust the iterator\n",
    "Otherwise return the result\n",
    "\n",
    "We can then simply iterate over the iterator until exhausted"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "46fbdd1d-8890-4b4a-8f77-7c116003f72b",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The first form of the iter() function\n",
    "\n",
    "We just studied the first form of the iter() function:\n",
    "\n",
    "iter(iterable) -> iterator for iterable\n",
    "\n",
    "if the iterable did not implement the iterator protocol, but implemented the sequence protocol\n",
    "iter() creates an iterator for us (leveraging the sequence protocol)\n",
    "Notice that the iter() function was able to generate an iterator for us automatically"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "raw",
   "id": "d13baa04-653b-4aea-905f-5eb5c04649c7",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The second form of the iter() function\n",
    "\n",
    "iter(callable, sentinel)\n",
    "\n",
    "This will return an iterator that will\n",
    "- call the callable when next() is called\n",
    "- and either raised StopIteration if result = sentinel value or return the result otherwise"
   ]
  },
  {
